items.title: Implementation of image resizing and non-max suppression in the Turi Create object detection pipeline.
items.body: In the paper by Redmon et. al. (https://arxiv.org/pdf/1506.02640.pdf), they describe the object detection pipeline as image resizing -> convolutional network -> non-max suppression (Figure 1). Are the resizing and non-max suppression algorithms intrinsic to the YOLO model from Redmon and colleagues (https://pjreddie.com/darknet/), or does Turi Create have to implement its own resizing and non-max suppression algorithms?

items.title: What dataset is used for pre-training the Turi Create TinyYOLO model?
items.body: Hi. What dataset is used for pre-training the TinyYOLO model used in Turi Create? Is it ImageNet as described in the paper by Redmon et. al (https://arxiv.org/pdf/1506.02640.pdf)?

items.title: module 'turicreate' has no attribute 'item_similarity_recommender'
items.body:
I have a problem, when I run my code in python, this attributeError is shown to me "module 'turicreate' has no attribute 'item_similarity_recommender'"

My python version: 3.7 My Windows: 7
Please help me. Thanks

my Code:

def model(train, name, user_id, item_id, target, users_to_recommend, n_rec, n_display):
    if name == 'cosine':
        model = tc.item_similarity_recommender.create(train, 
                                                    user_id=user_id, 
                                                    item_id=item_id, 
                                                    target=target, 
                                                    similarity_type='cosine')
    recom = model.recommend(users=users_to_recommend, k=n_rec)
    recom.print_rows(n_display)
    return model
name = 'cosine'
target = 'CountOfVisit'
cos = model(train, name, user_id, item_id, target, users_to_recommend, n_rec, n_display)

items.title: Can object detection model results vary with the same dataset?
items.body: Hi. Can model results slightly vary over time as the environment they are implemented in updates? Last year I trained an object detection model in Turi Create. I recently re-ran the model in Turi Create on the same testing dataset and I am getting slightly different results. Not much difference, just a few percentage points. Thanks for your help.

items.title: Object detector model `turicreate.object_detector.create` doesn't allow periodical saving of models before the training is over.
items.body:
I have been using turicreate's object detector model for a while now and what I have noticed is that it doesn't let me save models after every n iteration while the training is going on. 
I believe this is a very important feature to have as sometimes for a lot of reasons (hardware or software or other unpredicted reasons) the training gets killed and when it exits I don't even have a model which one might have spend hours training. 

I believe this part of the code is written in C++ and I am not that great with c++ but If pointed in the right direction I can pick this up and add this feature or if someone more experienced can pick it up that will be great too.

items.title: Using GPU with CUDA/cuDNN on WSL2
items.body:
I'm trying to train the [One Shot Object Detection example](https://apple.github.io/turicreate/docs/userguide/one_shot_object_detection/) using a GPU on WSL2 Ubuntu 18.04. Since #1108 CUDA now has support on WSL2. I've installed it and cuDNN and they work on other examples. I've also followed the instructions in [LinuxGPU.md](https://github.com/apple/turicreate/blob/master/LinuxGPU.md).

However, running the example does not seem to use the GPU at all, which I believe it should for this line:
```python
# Create a model. This step will take a few hours on CPU and about an hour on GPU
model = tc.one_shot_object_detector.create(starter_images, 'label')
```

Is there any way to verify whether turicreate is using the GPU? And if it actually isn't, how do I make it use my GPU on WSL2?
Thanks in advance!

items.title: Can I adjust the One-Shot synthetic augmentation logic?
items.body:
When I use the OSOD, I noticed the synthetic augmentation logic can't be suitable for me. 
For example:
1.It resize my starter image, but I don't need it especially it adjust the starter image size to so small to recognize.
2.I don't wanna apply yaw, pitch and roll rotation.

how to solve the problem?

items.title: killed at 771 iteration when training the model.
items.body:
I have prepared 18 images(5 classes) and used the default background to one shot create about 27k images dataset. The synthetic process done well. But when I load the synthetic images to train the model. It always was killed at the exactly 771 iterations. 
I have a CPU-based ubuntu system(version 20) with 8G ram and 35G swap. The tensorflow version is 2.2 and batch size is 35 by default. Anybody can help me?
BTW, I have used the default backgroud and 9 images(3 classes) to train an one shot object detection model successfully.

items.title: Input image format for ObjectDetector(Darknet-YOLO)
items.body:
In what format TuriCreate model expects an input image? Particularly I am interested in bias and a scale value. For example in CoreMLTools in some cases these parameters are specified explicitly:
```c
is_bgr: you typically need to set this to True for Caffe models
red_bias, blue_bias, green_bias: these will be added to the R, G, and B color values of each pixel
gray_bias: like the RGB biases but for grayscale images
image_scale: the pixel values will be multiplied by this number.
```
I wonder if something similar needs to be specified for TuriCreate for ObjectDetector(Darknet-YOLO(object detector))

items.title: Object Detection reduce false positives.
items.body:
HI, I'm using an object detector model and it works well and correctly identifies the desired object in most cases.

However it also wrongly identifies similar but different objects often with a high confidence.

I'm wondering what is the best strategy to improve this? Can I include images with no tags that don't have any of the desired object in them? A negative sample? Or should I start to tag similar objects so hopefully they will be identified as that and not the desired object?

Thanks.

items.title: tc.aggregate.QUANTILE does not meet "guaranteed" accuracy
items.body:
As mentioned in #745, tc.aggregate.QUANTILE is actually an approximation. According to the docstring: "quantiles are guaranteed to have 0.5% accuracy". However this does not seem to be true.
```python
import numpy as np                                                                                                                                   
import turicreate as tc

l = [-4, 10, -1, -100]
print(np.quantile(l, [.5])[0])

temp = tc.SFrame({'x': l})
temp['dummy'] = 1
result = temp.groupby('dummy', {'y': tc.aggregate.QUANTILE('x', 0.5)})
print(result['y'][0][0])
```
Produces:
```
-2.5
-1.0
```
-1.0 is not with 0.5% of -2.5.

items.title: A solution for those want to use turicreate with jupyter notebook but gets "ModuleNotFoundError: No module named 'turicreate'"; in Linux
items.body:
Assuming you want to use turicreate with both python2 and python3, here's a solution. I faced this problem even when I followed the official installation rules. I tried other solutions that I could find, but none of them worked. Here's the solution:

I am writing the fix for Ubuntu. If you're using another distro, your command will be slightly different according to your package manager.

sudo apt update
sudo apt remove virtualenv python jupyter
sudo apt install -y libstdc++6 python-setuptools libgconf-2-4
sudo apt install python-pip python3-pip
sudo pip install virtualenv notebook jupyter
sudo pip3 install virtualenv notebook jupyter
cd $HOME
virtualenv venv
cd venv/
source bin/activate
pip install --upgrade pip
pip install jupyter notebook
pip install -U turicreate
pip3 install jupyter notebook
pip3 install -U turicreate
jupyter notebook

items.title: Issue training with GPU on Linux
items.body:
Thank you for Turi Create. The style transfer API is really amazing. I am having trouble with training on a GPU with an AWS Ubuntu server. If anyone has any advice I would be very grateful.

Around October 2019 I was able to create an AWS Ubuntu server and train images on the GPU. It was blazing fast. I tried to repeat my set up this week May 2020, but now I have errors. I am sure versions of every dependency has updated or changed since I last built an environment using Linux to do the training or I am simply missing something new completely. The error I get is pasted at the end of this post.

Steps to reproduce the error are here...

1)
Choose an EC2 Amazon Machine Image (AMI)

items.title: Segfault when sframe fails to construct in pytest.
items.body:
Repro:

```python
import turicreate as tc

def test_sframe_wrong_path():
    tc.SFrame("willy-nilly")
```

Since `willy-nilly` is not an existing path, the constructor will fail and leave underlying C++ sframe to be default initialized, whose `planner node` is nullptr.

When the test is invoked by `pytest`, pytest tries to print the name for `self` after the constructor fails. Let's change `__repr__` of SFrame to return `Trevor_Noah` regardless. 

```python
import turicreate as tc

tc.SFrame.__repr__ = lambda self: "Trevor_Noah"

def test_sframe_wrong_path():
    tc.SFrame("willy-nilly")

```

information collected by pytest,

```python
self = Trevor_Noah, data = 'willy-nilly', format = 'auto', _proxy = None

    def __init__(self, data=None, format="auto", _proxy=None):
        """__init__(data=list(), format='auto')
        Construct a new SFrame from a url or a pandas.DataFrame.
        """
        # emit metrics for num_rows, num_columns, and type (local://, s3, hdfs, http)

```

the stack trace is printed but `self` is **not allowed** to use since it's uninitialized.

items.title: Saving to S3 assume key prefix already exists
items.body:
If I try to save an SFrame doing this `sf.save('s3://my-bucket/myFolder/mySFrameName')`, that will only work if the key prefix "myFolder/mySFrameName" already exists in my bucket. 

The best behavior here isn't clear to me, but certainly the current behavior is not right. If only `s3://my-bucket/myFolder/` exists than it should still have the SFrame.

I think we may want to be even more accepting, but I'm not sure. I think if the `myFolder` key prefix doesn't even exist, we should still save it to 's3://my-bucket/myFolder/mySFrameName'. Do other people have thoughts here?

items.title: SFrame chaining column manipulation?
items.body:
Is it possible to chain multiple commands for column manipulation?

Pandas Example:
```
df = (
    df
     .sort_values(["date", "hour"])
     .assign(date=lambda x: method(x))
)
```

In pandas you could do almost everything using this method, so it feels a bit cleaner than using equals multiple number of times.

```
df = df.sort_values(["date", "hour"])
df["date"] =  df["date"].apply(lambda x: method(x))
```

items.title: GroupBy uses a lot of memory
items.body:
I have a fairly large dataset, around 300GB in total.

`stack`, `apply`,  `unpack`, works pretty fast and uses minimal memory, usually in a few minutes, however the GroupBy function would increase memory usage to last least 60GB which crashed my 64GB machine constantly.

Is there a way to reduce memory consumption by GroupBy? Or an alternative method?

Currently thinking if I can instead do a unique on the key, and do a selection based on each unique, then doing some logic to recreate groupBy with something slower but uses less memory?

items.title: Fix update_version_number.sh script
items.body: The [update_version_number.sh](https://github.com/apple/turicreate/blob/master/scripts/update_version_number.sh) script only sucessfully updates the version number in [version_number.hpp](https://github.com/apple/turicreate/blob/master/src/model_server/lib/version.hpp). It should also update the version numbers in [setup.py](https://github.com/apple/turicreate/blob/master/src/python/setup.py) and [version_info.py](https://github.com/apple/turicreate/blob/master/src/python/turicreate/version_info.py).

items.title: Clear out temp files after using `tempfile.mkstemp`
items.body:
We are using `tempfile.mkstemp` without clearing out the temp files after use. 

> Unlike TemporaryFile(), the user of mkstemp() is responsible for deleting the temporary file when done with it.

https://docs.python.org/3/library/tempfile.html

Some places we use `tempfile.mkstemp`:

items.title: SFrame.apply() doesn't work for saving images
items.body:
For any SFrame with images in it, trying to save the images using an `apply` only saves a small fraction of the images in the SFrame, not all. The expected behavior should be that all images in the SFrame get saved.

To repro, take any SFrame with >100 images in it, and run:

```python
import turicreate as tc
sf = tc.SFrame('sframe_path.sframe')
sf["image"].apply(lambda im: im.save(id(im) + '.png'))
```

items.title: Do not call tensorflow.disable_v2_behavior()
items.body:
TuriCreate calls `tensorflow.disable_v2_behavior()`. For consistency, we're doing this every time we `import tensorflow`.

Calling this function disables v2 behavior **globally**. It prevents other parts of the TuriCreate from using v2 behavior. If users are also using TensorFlow directly in the same Python session as TuriCreate, this could break user code too.

items.title: Current S3 file system code path doesn't use Aws SigV4
items.body:
Related to #2278.

The `s3 region` can be set in the sigv4 auth body to find the right IAM to do the auth. We set s3 region by `TURI_S3_REGION` but the underlying code path doesn't pass the region info to s3.
